ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.

ElementDescription: Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Sex of subject at birth
Notes: M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported

ElementDescription: Visit name
Number of days from study baseline to date of visit
Would you like to spend more time with him / her (therapist) if you could?
Notes: 1 = NO, no time; 3 =  some more time; 5 = yes, MUCH more time

ElementDescription: You have met with him / her (therapist) for several weeks. Sometimes when you spend a lot of time with someone, you feel close to them. How close do you feel?
Notes: 1 = NOT close at all; 3 =  kind of close; 5 = VERY close

ElementDescription: How difficult was it for you and your family to travel here?
Notes: 1 = NOT difficult at all; 3 =  a little difficult; 5 = VERY difficult

ElementDescription: If you wanted to share a secret with an adult, would you share it with him / her (therapist)?
Notes: 1 = I WOULD NOT share it with him/her; 3 =  I might share it with him/her; 5 = I am sure I would share it with him/her

ElementDescription: How much did you like the rooms where you met with your therapist?
Notes: 1 = Didn't like the rooms at all; 3 =  the rooms were okay; 5 = I liked the rooms a lot

ElementDescription: How much do you like your therapist?
Notes: 1 = NOT at all; 3 =  sometimes I like him/her sometimes I don't; 5 = I like him/her VERY much

ElementDescription: Sometimes, young people don't like the way adults dress. Did you like the clothes that your therapist wore to your meetings?
Notes: 1 = Didn't like the clothes at all; 3 =  the clothes were ok; 5 = I liked the clothes a lot

ElementDescription: Did you think it was difficult to talk with him / her (therapist)?
Notes: 1 = Was not difficult at all; 3 =  sometimes it was difficult, but sometimes it was not but sometimes it was not; 5 = Was VERY difficult

ElementDescription: Would you invite him / her (therapist) to eat lunch with you?
Notes: 1 = I would not invite him/her:3 =  I might invite him/her:5 = I am sure I would invite him/her

ElementDescription: If you had a very bad day at school, would he / she (therapist) be one of the people you would want to talk to about it?
Notes: 1 = I would not talk to him/her:3 =  I might talk to him/her about it:5 = I would talk to him/her for sure

ElementDescription: Reverse-scored
CPTR Total Score
Notes: sum(CPTR1, CPTR2, CPTR4, CPTR6, CPTR7, CPTR8REV, CPTR9, CPTR10)

ElementDescription: CPTR Average Score
Child's Perception of Therapist Rating - Total Score
Notes: sum(CPTR1, CPTR2, CPTR3REV, CPTR4, CPTR5, CPTR6, CPTR7, CPTR8REV, CPTR9, CPTR10)

ElementDescription: Child's Perception of Therapist Rating - Average Score
Notes: mean(CPTR1, CPTR2, CPTR3REV, CPTR4, CPTR5, CPTR6, CPTR7, CPTR8REV, CPTR9, CPTR10)

ElementDescription: Therapist type
Notes: 0 = IE (Independent Evaluator); 1 = PT (Pharmacotherapist); 2 = CBT (Cognitive Behavioral Therapist); 3 = MD (Medical Doctor); 4 = PI (Principal Investigator)

ElementDescription: Indicator noting imputed data set number
